-- в”Ђв”Ђ Linode в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Cloud hosting and VPS provider offering Linux virtual machines, storage, and Kubernetes, now operating as Akamai Cloud Computing.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Usage-based$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$5/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2003, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Part of Akamai Technologies (thousands of employees; Linode had 200+ pre-acquisition)$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, United States (pre-acquisition); now part of Akamai, Cambridge, Massachusetts$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Linode Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Linode (Akamai Cloud) review 2026: VPS hosting, compute, storage and Kubernetes pricing from $5/month. Features, plans and top alternatives compared.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Linode is a cloud hosting and virtual private server (VPS) provider founded in 2003 by Christopher Aker, a Full Sail University graduate, making it one of the oldest independent cloud infrastructure companies still in continuous operation before its acquisition. The name is a portmanteau of 'Linux' and 'node,' reflecting the company's original focus on providing affordable Linux-based virtual machines to developers, a market it helped pioneer alongside early competitors like Rackspace and, later, DigitalOcean. The company began operating out of California, relocated to Galloway, New Jersey in 2008, and settled its headquarters in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania in 2018, occupying the historic Corn Exchange National Bank building. Over nearly two decades as an independent company, Linode expanded well beyond basic VPS hosting to include high-memory and GPU-enabled compute instances, block storage and automated backups, Longview performance monitoring (launched 2013), S3-compatible object storage (added October 2019), and a managed Kubernetes engine, LKE (added November 2019), building a full developer-oriented cloud platform while maintaining a reputation for simple, transparent, flat-rate pricing compared to hyperscalers like AWS or Google Cloud. On February 15, 2022, Akamai Technologies announced its intent to acquire Linode for approximately $900 million, a deal that closed in March 2022; Akamai's stated rationale was to combine Linode's developer-friendly, distributed compute platform with Akamai's global edge network, CDN, and security infrastructure to better compete for cloud workloads that benefit from being close to end users. Akamai completed a full rebrand from Linode to 'Akamai Cloud Computing' (also referred to as Akamai Connected Cloud) in February 2023, retaining the underlying Linode product line and its familiar simple pricing model while adding Akamai's edge, DDoS protection, and CDN capabilities on top, and expanding the combined platform's data center footprint to 41-plus regions globally. Despite the corporate rebrand, the product is still widely referred to by its original name, and its pricing, developer console, and API have remained largely consistent with the pre-acquisition Linode experience, which is an important continuity point for long-time customers. Pricing is usage-based and notably simple relative to hyperscale clouds: shared-CPU compute instances start at $5 per month for a Nanode with 1 vCPU, 1 GB RAM, 25 GB SSD storage, and 1 TB of outbound transfer, billed hourly with a monthly cap so costs never exceed the advertised flat rate. Higher tiers scale up through larger shared-CPU plans, dedicated-CPU instances for predictable performance, high-memory plans, and GPU instances for machine learning workloads, alongside separate pricing for block storage, object storage, managed databases, load balancers, and LKE Kubernetes clusters (control plane free, nodes billed as standard compute instances). New sign-ups are frequently offered promotional cloud credits (commonly around $100) to trial the platform. Linode's target audience is developers, startups, and small-to-mid-size engineering teams who want straightforward, predictable-cost Linux cloud infrastructure without the complexity and pricing opacity of AWS, Azure, or Google Cloud Platform, as well as businesses that value its long-standing reputation for responsive human support and a clean, minimal control panel. Its primary competitors are DigitalOcean and Vultr in the developer-friendly VPS segment, along with Hetzner in the budget-cloud space, and the three major hyperscalers for larger enterprise workloads. Linode differentiates itself through its two-decade operating history and developer trust, transparent flat-rate billing, and, post-acquisition, the unique combination of simple VPS-style compute with Akamai's enterprise-grade global edge and security network layered on top, a combination none of its direct VPS-tier competitors currently offer at the same scale.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'afcd955c-740d-4ea0-8ee5-e3052c431a5d';

