-- в”Ђв”Ђ Listmonk в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Free, open-source, self-hosted newsletter and mailing list manager built as a single high-performance Go binary.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free / Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2019, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Listmonk Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Listmonk review 2026: free, self-hosted newsletter and mailing list manager built in Go. Features, setup, pricing, and alternatives to Mailchimp compared.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Listmonk is a free, open-source, self-hosted newsletter and mailing list management platform created by Kailash Nadh, an Indian software developer who serves as the Chief Technology Officer of Zerodha, India's largest stock brokerage. The project originated from a practical internal need: Zerodha required a way to send large volumes of transactional and marketing email to millions of subscribers each month without paying the escalating per-subscriber fees charged by hosted platforms like Mailchimp, and without handing subscriber data to a third party. Nadh built listmonk to solve that problem in-house, then open-sourced it, and it is used in production at Zerodha to send millions of emails monthly, giving the project a rare degree of real-world, high-volume battle-testing uncommon for a community open-source tool. Architecturally, listmonk is distributed as a single compiled binary (available for Linux, Windows, macOS, and BSD variants), which dramatically simplifies deployment compared to typical web applications that require separate runtime environments, dependency managers, and multi-service orchestration. The backend is written in Go, chosen for its performance and low resource footprint, while the administrative dashboard frontend is built with Vue.js. The only external dependency is a PostgreSQL database, which listmonk uses both as its data store and, notably, as a query engine, letting administrators write raw SQL to define highly specific subscriber segments rather than being limited to a fixed set of filter dropdowns common in SaaS competitors. Resource requirements are deliberately minimal: the project reports running on a fraction of a single CPU core and around 57 MB of peak RAM even at meaningful scale, making it viable on very cheap VPS instances. Deployment is most commonly done via Docker Compose, though the single-binary distribution also supports direct installation, and one-click deployment options exist on platforms like Railway and PikaPods. Core features include support for both single and double opt-in mailing lists scaling to millions of subscribers per instance, SQL-based subscriber querying and segmentation for precise audience targeting, multiple campaign content authoring options (a drag-and-drop visual builder, a WYSIWYG rich text editor, Markdown, raw HTML, or plain text), built-in campaign analytics covering opens, clicks, bounces, and link-level tracking, and a transactional email API that lets developers send individually triggered messages (password resets, receipts, notifications) through the same infrastructure as bulk campaigns. It supports multiple SMTP provider configurations with per-provider rate limiting and queueing to manage deliverability and avoid provider throttling, and it extends beyond email through a messenger webhook system that can push notifications to SMS gateways, WhatsApp, or Firebase Cloud Messaging (FCM). A full REST API exposes essentially every feature programmatically, and OIDC-based single sign-on with role-based access permissions supports team and enterprise deployments. Because listmonk is licensed under the GNU Affero General Public License v3 (AGPLv3) and distributed with no commercial tier, it carries no subscription cost, per-subscriber fee, or send-volume fee; the only expense is the self-hosting infrastructure and any transactional email/SMTP relay service used to actually deliver messages (such as Amazon SES, Postmark, or SendGrid). This pricing model is listmonk's single biggest differentiator from hosted competitors like Mailchimp, ConvertKit, or Klaviyo, which charge scaling fees tied directly to subscriber count or email volume; a listmonk deployment's cost stays roughly flat regardless of list size, aside from server sizing and SMTP relay costs. The target audience includes developers and engineering-minded teams comfortable self-hosting infrastructure, cost-sensitive newsletter publishers and bloggers with large lists where per-subscriber SaaS pricing becomes expensive, companies needing full data ownership of subscriber PII for compliance or privacy reasons, and organizations sending transactional email who want that traffic on the same platform as their marketing campaigns. Its closest open-source competitors are Mautic and Sendy (also self-hosted, PHP-based, and paired with external SMTP relays), while its primary hosted competitors are Mailchimp, ConvertKit, Klaviyo, and Brevo. Listmonk differentiates itself through its single-binary Go architecture (versus the heavier PHP/MySQL stacks of most self-hosted alternatives), its unusually high documented scale (Zerodha's millions-of-emails-per-month production usage), its SQL-native segmentation, and its complete absence of subscriber-based pricing.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '84142957-2683-4f6e-9088-2169508d193b';

